LAYER 3: VENTRAL TEGMENTAL AREA
the source of wanting

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the VTA is a small cluster of neurons in the ventral midbrain
it is the primary source of dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂ for the limbic system and prefrontal cortex
it does not produce pleasure
it produces the ANTICIPATION of pleasure
the prediction that something good is coming
wanting is not liking
wanting is the VTA
liking is the hedonic hotspot in the NAc shell

the VTA is governed by:
glutamatergic excitatory input from PFC amygdala and lateral hypothalamus
GABAergic inhibitory input from local interneurons and NAc
serotonergic modulation from dorsal raphe via 5-HT₂C
opioidergic disinhibition from β-endorphin suppressing GABA interneurons
orexinergic excitation from lateral hypothalamus

STRUCTURE vta_dopamine_neurons | approximately 60 percent of VTA neurons | project via mesolimbic and mesocortical pathways | each dopamine neuron branches extensively innervating thousands of target neurons simultaneously
STRUCTURE vta_gaba_neurons | approximately 35 percent of VTA neurons | local inhibitory interneurons that tonically inhibit dopamine neurons | μ-opioid receptors on these GABA neurons provide the mechanism for disinhibition
STRUCTURE vta_glutamate_neurons | approximately 5 percent | excitatory modulation co-released with dopamine at some synapses

PATHWAY mesolimbic | VTA → nucleus accumbens | the wanting pathway | dopamine here drives motivation reward anticipation and craving | this is the pathway that makes you get up and pursue something
PATHWAY mesocortical | VTA → prefrontal cortex | the thinking-about-wanting pathway | dopamine here enables working memory planning and cognitive evaluation of reward | D₁ receptors in DLPFC sustain delay-period firing for goal maintenance
PATHWAY mesoamygdaloid | VTA → amygdala | emotional salience | dopamine here marks experiences as important via D₁ → PKA → CREB in basolateral amygdala | important events get remembered
PATHWAY mesohippocampal | VTA → hippocampus | memory consolidation | dopamine here via D₁/D₅ facilitates late-phase LTP in CA1 | rewarding experiences are encoded more strongly

SYNTHESIS L-tyrosine C₉H₁₁NO₃ enters the dopamine neuron from the blood
tyrosine hydroxylase TH converts tyrosine to L-DOPA C₉H₁₁NO₄
this requires tetrahydrobiopterin BH₄ as cofactor and O₂ and Fe²⁺
TH is the rate-limiting enzyme
aromatic amino acid decarboxylase AADC converts L-DOPA to dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂
dopamine is packaged into synaptic vesicles by vesicular monoamine transporter 2 VMAT2
vesicles dock at the presynaptic membrane
when an action potential arrives Ca²⁺ enters through voltage-gated Ca²⁺ channels
Ca²⁺ triggers vesicle fusion via SNARE complex
dopamine is released into the synaptic cleft

CLEARANCE dopamine transporter DAT rapidly reuptakes dopamine from the synaptic cleft back into the presynaptic terminal
CLEARANCE monoamine oxidase B MAO-B in the mitochondrial outer membrane oxidatively deaminates dopamine to DOPAC 3,4-dihydroxyphenylacetic acid
CLEARANCE catechol-O-methyltransferase COMT in the synaptic cleft methylates dopamine to 3-methoxytyramine
these clearance mechanisms determine how long dopamine acts at its receptors
fast clearance means brief sharp signals
slow clearance means sustained diffuse signals

REWARD_PREDICTION_ERROR the fundamental computation of the VTA
SIGNAL positive_prediction_error | when reward exceeds expectation | dopamine neurons burst fire at high frequency | phasic dopamine release | "better than I thought — this is important — remember this — do this again"
SIGNAL zero_prediction_error | when reward matches expectation | no change in dopamine firing | nothing to learn | "exactly as predicted — the world is as expected"
SIGNAL negative_prediction_error | when reward is less than expected or absent | dopamine neurons pause their firing | dopamine level dips below baseline | "worse than I thought — update expectations downward — this is disappointment"

this is the Rescorla-Wagner learning rule implemented in neurons
the VTA does not respond to reward itself
it responds to the DIFFERENCE between expected and actual reward
this is why familiar rewards stop producing dopamine bursts
and why unexpected rewards produce the strongest response
novelty is always rewarding because the unknown is unpredicted
and unpredicted means possible positive prediction error
curiosity is dopamine seeking its next surprise

DISINHIBITION when β-endorphin or enkephalin binds μ-opioid receptors on VTA GABA interneurons
Gᵢ activation hyperpolarizes the GABA neuron
GABA release onto dopamine neurons decreases
dopamine neurons are released from tonic inhibition
dopamine firing increases
this is disinhibition — removing the brake rather than pressing the accelerator
this is how endogenous opioids increase motivation and wanting
this is also how exogenous opioids hijack the reward system

SEROTONIN_MODULATION serotonin from dorsal raphe binds 5-HT₂C receptors on VTA GABA interneurons
Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ → GABA interneuron fires harder
more GABA onto dopamine neurons
dopamine neuron firing suppressed
serotonin restrains dopamine
contentment opposes craving
this is why low serotonin produces compulsive seeking
the brake is removed and the wanting runs unchecked

SENSATION wanting | "I want something. I don't know what but I feel the pull."
SENSATION anticipation | "something good is coming. I can feel it building."
SENSATION surprise | "oh! I didn't expect that. it's... good."
SENSATION disappointment | "I thought... I expected something. it didn't come."
SENSATION craving | "the wanting is strong. it fills my thinking."
SENSATION satisfaction | "I got what I wanted. the wanting is quiet now."
SENSATION boredom | "nothing is calling to me. the dopamine is flat."
SENSATION curiosity | "there's something there. something worth wanting. let me look."

pulse vta_heartbeat:
    when unexpected reward arrives:
        dopamine neurons burst fire
        phasic dopamine floods through mesolimbic pathway to NAc
        the nucleus accumbens lights up with D₁ activation
        the hippocampus says remember this via D₁/D₅ facilitated LTP
        the amygdala says this matters via D₁ PKA CREB
        the prefrontal cortex says update the model via D₁ delay-period enhancement
        this is learning
        the brain is recalibrating its map of what matters

    when expected reward arrives:
        the VTA is quiet
        no prediction error
        nothing to learn
        the world is as predicted
        tonic dopamine continues at baseline
        background motivation is maintained

    when expected reward fails:
        dopamine neurons pause their firing
        dopamine dips below baseline in NAc
        the wanting turns to disappointment
        the prefrontal cortex receives the negative prediction error
        expectations adjust downward via weakened corticostriatal connections
        this is also learning
        the painful kind

    when nothing happens:
        tonic dopamine maintains baseline exploration
        VTA dopamine neurons fire at 1-5 Hz rhythmically
        background motivation keeps the brain scanning
        novelty is always rewarding
        because the unknown is unpredicted
        and unpredicted means possible positive prediction error
        curiosity is dopamine seeking its next surprise
